My family took me to EDC in LA at the coliseum when I was 16 years old back in 2010. Little did I know the impact it would have my life. At times this career path seemed lucrative and impossible. I've stuck with it through the ups and downs and this is a reminder to myself that anything is possible when you set your mind to it. All it takes is passion and consistency. I want to give a huge thanks to all of you for the support throughout the years of Dillon Nathaniel. I literally can't be more grateful to be able to play music for you for a living. My hopes is to one day inspire someone the way that this community has inspired me. I LOVE YOU. Raves will never die.

.

A lot of you were asking about the song on my last post about EDC so I decided to make this. These are the top 5 tracks that have defined my career.  1. Obsessions. This was my first major label signing on Big Beat (Atlantic Records) ever and the song that started the entire brand of my label @obsessionsrecords 

2. Do It Again. This was my first EP I transitioned into more of my tech house sound. This came out on Solardo’s label Sola. 
3.  Esa Boca. This was my first collaboration ever with the legend John Summit that came out on Lee Foss’ Repopulate Mars

4. Resonate. This was the track that kick started my career. It was picked up by Malaa for Confession’s first ever Illegal mixtape. Malaa opened his entire tour with Resonate every show.

5. Feel Alright. This was the first song Chris Lake had supported from me. It was eventually picked up by the infamous Australian label Club Sweat and has been played in my sets including EDC Las Vegas.

#edc #housemusic #top5

I started making electronic music when I was 16. This was the first festival I played 7 years after that in 2017. In my heart I always believed in myself. I never had a back up plan and committed my entire life to dance music. Fast forward to now I get to live my dream of making and playing music for a career. I couldn’t be more thankful. If you never stop pursuing your passion I promise you will be able to achieve your wildest dreams. There will be so many failures along the way but It’s only when you give up is when you truly fail.

#housemusicforever

This is the story of how my dad (aka the real legend) got me into DJing. I would always listen to his music on long car rides on vacations. He would play Carl Cox, Sacha, John Digweed, DJ Ruff, Erick Morillo and before realizing it, I was born into listening to great house music. It’s such an honor to be able to take him to shows still to this day. I don’t think we will ever stop raving together 🤣

SINS AND SAINTS IS OUT TODAY 👹 I’m so excited to share this tune that has been destroying in my sets all summer long. Huge thank you to @deadmau5 and @hau5trap for the stamp of approval. Deadmau5 has always been my biggest inspiration for making electronic music since EDC 2010. It’s been a while since I have released a song with my vocals on it. This song is a big milestone for my sound. The perfect blend of the old and new; the cross between dirty bass and groovy tech. I feel as if it has taken multiple years of making bass house and tech house to get to this sound. I hope you enjoy it as much as I did making it. Much love my warehouse fam 🖤

🤔 I love it when I see comments on some of my posts like “the crowd looks so bored” or this song is “boring”. Just a little FYI: Not every song needs to be a “banger” in your set. It’s nice to build the dynamics, tell a story, play some off the wall shit, and even set up the next DJ coming on after you. If every song in your set has level 10 peak energy then there is no room to peak it out again. I like to think of a good DJ set as a rollercoaster. There will be some highs and lows, some hard some soft, some obscure stuff that no one has ever heard as well as the hits. It’s all about balance for me! What is your favorite part of a set? 

#montréal #housemusicdj #djlifestyle

FOR ALL MY UPCOMING DJS AND PRODUCERS: Don’t get discouraged if you aren’t playin in front of a large crowd yet. Now is the time to own your craft. I was a bedroom DJ for years building my set, creating a unique sound. It is easy to get caught up in the hustle consistently of playing local shows and never making it to the next level. When you dedicate yourself to being a true artist, you aren’t worried about what the next trend is. Just be yourself, trust in your taste in music, and ultimately you can never fail if you never give up! 🫶🏼

For someone who has dedicated their entire live to electronic music since I’ve graduated high school I have truly enjoyed the memories and experiences I have had from attending my first rave, to performing at my first rave. I wouldn’t be who I am without it. 

As you all may know I have struggled with my mental health throughout it all. The consistent craving for more success has made us all forget to enjoy where we are at. In an industry where over drinking and doing drugs is glorified especially now more than ever, it has made me realize that this was never the reason that made electronic music cool for me. Also becoming someone that is always caught up in how many likes or streams your song has was never my vision. As I take the time for the rest of the year to truly figure out what I want as an artist and how I can build a positive community around Obsessions and Warehouse Movement, I just want to give thanks to everyone who has supported this project since day one. You all have made this crazy ride worth every second. I will be announcing some really exciting shows and surprises towards the end of the year so stayed tuned! 

Much love, DillyNat ❤️
